05956nam a22006975i 9780822377115DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20142013ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223771157 a10.1515/97808223771152doi  a(DE-B1597)553937  a(OCoLC)972042804  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aPHI0310002bisacsh04aThe Privatization of Hope :bErnst Bloch and the Future of Utopia, SIC 8 /ced. by Slavoj Zizek, Peter Thompson. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2014] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSIC : 3 ;v800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Editions and Translations -- tPreface: Bloch’s Ontology of Not-Yet- Being -- tIntroduction: The Privatization of Hope and the Crisis of Negation -- t1 Bloch and a Philosophy of the Proterior -- t2 An Anti-humanist Utopia? -- t3 Ernst Bloch’s Dialectical Anthropology -- t4 Religion, Utopia, and the Metaphysics of Contingency -- t5 The Privatization of Eschatology and Myth: Ernst Bloch vs. Rudolph Bultmann -- t6 The Education of Hope: On the Dialectical Potential of Speculative Materialism -- t7 Engendering the Future: Bloch’s Utopian Philosophy in Dialogue with Gender Theory -- t8 The Zero-Point: Encountering the Dark Emptiness of Nothingness -- t9 A Marxist Poetics: Allegory and Reading in The Principle of Hope -- t10 Singing Summons the Existence of the Fountain: Bloch, Music, and Utopia -- t11 Transforming Utopian into Metopian Systems: Bloch’s Principle of Hope Revisited -- t12 Unlearning How to Hope: Eleven Theses in Defense of Liberal Democracy and Consumer Culture -- t13 Can We Hope to Walk Tall in a Computerized World of Work? -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe concept of hope is central to the work of the German philosopher Ernst Bloch (1885–1977), especially in his magnum opus, The Principle of Hope (1959). The "speculative materialism" that he first developed in the 1930s asserts a commitment to humanity's potential that continued through his later work. In The Privatization of Hope, leading thinkers in utopian studies explore the insights that Bloch's ideas provide in understanding the present. Mired in the excesses and disaffections of contemporary capitalist society, hope in the Blochian sense has become atomized, desocialized, and privatized. From myriad perspectives, the contributors clearly delineate the renewed value of Bloch's theories in this age of hopelessness. Bringing Bloch's "ontology of Not Yet Being" into conversation with twenty-first-century concerns, this collection is intended to help revive and revitalize philosophy's commitment to the generative force of hope.Contributors. Roland Boer, Frances Daly, Henk de Berg, Vincent Geoghegan, Wayne Hudson, Ruth Levitas, David Miller, Catherine Moir, Caitríona Ní Dhúill, Welf Schröter, Johan Siebers, Peter Thompson, Francesca Vidal, Rainer Ernst Zimmermann, Slavoj Žižek  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / General.2bisacsh1 aBerg, Henk de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoer, Roland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaly, Frances, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeoghegan, Vincent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHudson, Wayne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevitas, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoir, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1